related_questions.question: What does flaxseed do to your body?
related_questions.snippet: Flaxseed is commonly used to improve digestive health or relieve constipation. Flaxseed may also help lower total blood cholesterol and low-density lipoprotein (LDL, or "bad") cholesterol levels, which may help reduce the risk of heart disease.
related_questions.title: Flaxseed: Is ground better than whole? - Mayo Clinic

related_questions.question: Who should not take flaxseed?
related_questions.snippet: Women with breast, uterine, and ovarian cancer or endometriosis should ask their doctor before taking flaxseed, because it may act like estrogen in the body. Some researchers think pregnant women should not take flaxseed, because it may act like estrogen in the body.
related_questions.title: Flaxseed Information | Mount Sinai - New York

related_questions.question: Is it safe to eat flaxseed every day?
related_questions.snippet: While there's no specific portion recommendation for flaxseed, 1–2 tablespoons per day is considered a healthy amount. One tablespoon of ground flaxseed contains 37 calories and 2 grams of polyunsaturated fat, including omega-3 fatty acids, 0.5 grams of monounsaturated fat and 2 grams of dietary fiber.
related_questions.title: Flaxseed: Nutritionally powerful - Mayo Clinic Health System

related_questions.question: What does flaxseed do for the female body?
related_questions.snippet: Flaxseeds Balance Oestrogen Levels Flaxseeds contain lignans, which can help to balance oestrogen levels in the body. This can be beneficial for women with oestrogen-dominant conditions like breast cancer, fibroids, or endometriosis.

hover_info.info: Alpha-linolenic acid (ALA) is an essential omega-3 fatty acid found in nuts such as walnuts. It is necessary for normal human growth and development. Alpha-linolenic acid is thought to decrease the risk of heart disease by helping to maintain normal heart rhythm and pumping. It might also reduce blood clots.

answer_box.snippet: Overview. Flax (Linum usitatissimum) is a food and fiber crop. Flaxseeds are a good source of dietary fiber and omega-3 fatty acids, including alpha-linolenic acid. Flaxseeds also contain phytoestrogens called lignans, which are similar to the hormone estrogen. The fiber in flaxseed is found in the seed coat.

buttons.subtitle: What Does Flax Seed Do To The Body
buttons.title: The Benefits of Flaxseed - WebMD
buttons.snippet: Some of the other components in flaxseed also have antioxidant properties, which may contribute to protection against cancer and heart disease. Research suggests that plant omega-3s help the cardiovascular system through several different mechanisms, including anti-inflammatory action and normalizing the heartbeat.
snippet_highlighted_words: antioxidant properties, which may contribute to protection against cancer and heart disease

buttons.subtitle: When Should You Not Eat Flaxseed
buttons.title: Flaxseed and flaxseed oil - Mayo Clinic
buttons.snippet: Avoid use of flaxseed and flaxseed oil during pregnancy. Occasionally, using flaxseed or flaxseed oil causes an allergic reaction. Don't eat raw or unripe flaxseeds. Because flaxseed oil might decrease blood clotting, stop using flaxseed oil two weeks before having elective surgery.

buttons.subtitle: How To Eat Flaxseed?
buttons.title: Flaxseed: Is ground better than whole? - Mayo Clinic
buttons.snippet: Add a tablespoon of ground flaxseed to your hot or cold breakfast cereal. Add a teaspoon of ground flaxseed to mayonnaise or mustard when making a sandwich. Mix a tablespoon of ground flaxseed into an 8-ounce container of yogurt. Bake ground flaxseed into cookies, muffins, breads and other baked goods.
snippet_highlighted_words: Add a tablespoon of ground flaxseed to your hot or cold breakfast cereal

buttons.title: Flaxseed: 9 Health Benefits and How to Eat - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Flaxseed is rich in protein, fiber, and omega-3 fatty acids and contains several important vitamins and minerals that can support your overall health. Its nutrients may offer some protection against cancer and help reduce your cholesterol, blood pressure, and blood sugar when consumed as part of a balanced diet.

buttons.subtitle: Who Cannot Take Flaxseed
buttons.title: Flaxseed Information | Mount Sinai - New York
buttons.snippet: Ask your doctor before taking flaxseed if you are pregnant or breastfeeding. Men with prostate cancer should ask their doctor before taking flaxseed. People with a bowel obstruction, inflamed bowel, or narrowed esophagus should not take flaxseed. It is high in fiber and could make the condition worse.

buttons.snippet: Flaxseeds are also an excellent source of protein and dietary fiber. Like other foods that are high in soluble fiber, ground flaxseeds can help keep LDL cholesterol in check, improve digestive health, and alleviate constipation. To maximize the health benefits of flaxseeds, be sure to grind them before eating.

buttons.subtitle: What Are Flax Seeds High In
buttons.title: Flax Seeds 101: Nutrition Facts and Health Benefits - Healthline
buttons.snippet: Omega-3 fatty acids Flax seeds are very high in the omega-3 fatty acid alpha-linolenic acid (ALA). They have been shown to decrease heart disease risk in animal studies by reducing inflammation in the arteries ( 47 ). Several studies link ALA with a lower risk of stroke, heart attacks, and chronic kidney disease.
